	<p>
		Hello! I am <strong>Pranavanath Balamurali</strong>, a first-year Electrical and Computer Engineering (ECE) student at the University of Texas at Austin. I operate at the intersection of hardware optimization, physics-driven machine learning, and systemic, calculation-first decision models. This digital space serves as an open architecture portfolio and an uncompromising technical ledger for my research, engineering implementations, and analytical writing.
	</p>

	<h2>Academic Vector & Research Nuance</h2>
	<p>
		My primary research and technical focus centers heavily on <strong>Scientific Machine Learning (SciML)</strong>, specifically targeting automated compact model synthesis for advanced semiconductor nodes. I am deeply interested in decoupling tightly bound physical constraints by combining structural domain knowledge with deep learning architectures.
	</p>
	<p>
		A core example of this is my work on <strong>PRISM-UDE</strong>, a framework designed for the automated compact model synthesis of 3nm FinFET transistors. By leveraging <strong>Universal Differential Equations (UDEs)</strong> and <strong>Physics-Informed Neural Networks (PINNs)</strong>, I work on embedding neural network layers (implemented using Julia ecosystems like <code>Lux.jl</code> and <code>Zygote.jl</code> for custom backpropagation) directly inside physical differential equations. This allows us to capture complex, highly non-linear short-channel effects and MOSFET dynamics without sacrificing the physical interpretability required for SPICE-level simulations. I use symbolic regression to extract closed-form analytical equations from these trained neural components, bridging the gap between raw black-box accuracy and clean semiconductor physics.
	</p>
	<p>
		On the hardware and embedded side, my work scales from high-level regressions down to bare metal. Recently, this included engineering <strong>WeatherMind</strong>, an IoT edge-computing weather prediction system utilizing an ESP32 microcontroller integrated with neural network inference, as well as developing a hardware-accelerated microclimate frost prediction system tailored for precise agricultural automated training loops.
	</p>

	<h2>Cognitive Architecture & Systemic Analysis</h2>
	<p>
		I approach competitive, strategic, and creative systems through an identical analytical lens, a reflection of a cognitive profile weighted heavily toward a high spatial IQ (in the 140–150 range). I value concrete calculation, spatial reasoning, and structural patterns over volatile intuition or rigid rote memorization. This framework governs my deep-seated interests outside the lab:
	</p>
	<ul>
		<li>
			<strong>Positional Chess Theory:</strong> Operating as an advanced competitive player (maintaining a 2100 Rapid and ~1600 Blitz rating on Chess.com), I subscribe to a strict positional style. I am drawn to structural, low-calculation openings that rely on long-term systemic pressures rather than sharp, volatile theory. My repertoire book, <em>Effortless Openings</em>, focuses precisely on this philosophy—using standard Italian Game and Quiet Giuoco Pianissimo frameworks (such as the flexible $c3$/$d3$ pawn structures and the $f1$-$g3$ knight maneuvers) to systematically out-read opponents through patient calculation.
		</li>
		<li>
			<strong>Macroeconomics & Semiconductor Geopolitics:</strong> I analyze the global macroeconomic forces and supply-chain vulnerabilities that dictate the manufacturing landscape of next-generation hardware. Mapping out the geopolitical friction points surrounding sub-7nm fabrication facilities is, to me, simply another macroscopic optimization problem.
		</li>
		<li>
			<strong>Tennis & Biometric Optimization:</strong> I track professional tennis strictly through the lenses of physics, geometric court positioning, and mechanical efficiency. To me, the sustained dominance of an athlete like Novak Djokovic represents the ultimate mathematical optimization of physical resilience, technical precision, and biomechanical economy.
		</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Aesthetics, Lifestyle, & Creative Intersections</h2>
	<p>
		Outside of engineering and competitive strategy, my daily life and creative pursuits follow a philosophy of clean lines and structured design:
	</p>
	<ul>
		<li>
			<strong>Music Theory & Raga Classification:</strong> I enjoy exploring the mathematical relationships within music composition, specifically mapping the structural symmetries between Western church modes and traditional Carnatic ragas (such as analyzing melodies within the rigorous frameworks of ragas like <em>Varamu</em>).
		</li>
		<li>
			<strong>Lifestyle & Design:</strong> I maintain an active lifestyle as a competitive swimmer, a vegetarian diet (incorporating eggs), and a clean, tailored minimalist style inspired by classic, casual aesthetics. Whether writing clean script, touch-typing to optimize my WPM ceiling, or building responsive UI layouts, I prioritize efficiency and functional elegance.
		</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Projected Horizons</h3>
	<p>
		My long-term objectives are rooted squarely in advanced artificial intelligence and hardware synthesis. I am tailoring my current research trajectory toward pursuing future AI research roles at Google, specifically aiming for Research Scientist or Research Engineer tracks within teams like Google DeepMind or Google Research. This blog tracks that progression—one step, equation, and optimization layer at a time.
	</p>
